"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229211","Department for Transport","false","2015-03-25","<p>The Counter Fraud Committee has been in place since 2011 in its current guise.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-03-25T15:03:00.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229211/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229211/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-03-23","Highways Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 19 March 2015 to Question 227614, when the Counter Fraud Committee of the Highways Agency was created.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","228722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229212","Department for Transport","false","2015-03-25","<p>The Counter Fraud Committee reports to each Audit Committee meeting. Its meetings are arranged so that appropriate discussion and any additional action can be taken before the Audit Committee meets.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-03-25T14:56:26.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229212/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229212/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-03-23","Highways Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 19 March 2015 to Question 227614, how frequently the Counter Fraud Committee submits reports to the Audit Committee of the Highways Agency.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","228720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229213","Department for Transport","false","2015-03-25","<p>As an executive agency, assurance is provided to the Secretary Of State through the accounting officer via the principal accounting officer, The Permanent Secretary. Each year the Audit Committee conducts an assessment of their effectiveness using the National Audit Office checklist that supports best practice for Audit Committees. Results of this are published in the annual report and discussed by the board through the chairman’s annual report.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-03-25T14:59:50.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229213/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229213/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-03-23","Highways Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 19 March 2015 to Question 227614, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the remit and powers of the Audit Committee of the Highways Agency.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","228721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229214","Department for Transport","false","2015-03-25","<p>Since 1 July 2013, grievance policy and procedures for Highways Agency has been aligned to the Department of Transport. This includes a number of guiding principles as follows:-</p><p> </p><p>1. The objective is resolution of the grievance</p><p>2. Find out what outcome the person is seeking.</p><p>3. Take a balanced approach in considering the grievance.</p><p>4. Explain your decisions.</p><p>5. Consider the matter on the basis of current policy.</p><p>6. Make a decision in a reasonable time.</p><p>7. Ask for any documents that you think will help you.</p><p> </p><p>It is for the Decision Officer appointed to the grievance to decide how to carry out each specific investigation, advised as necessary by the HR Casework Team.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-03-25T15:24:06.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229214/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229214/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-03-23","Highways Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what guidelines he has set out for the Highways Agency on that body's process for completing grievance investigations.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","228729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229215","Department for Transport","false","2015-03-25","<p>The reports form part of the internal control framework of the Highways Agency. The report of the Counter Fraud Committee (CFC) is a standing item on the Audit Committee (AC) agenda, which until recently were provided orally, given that the chair of the AC also attends CFC. More recently these have been provided as a written report to the AC to facilitate follow up questions from other AC members. Each year an annual CFC report is produced for the AC which informs the year end assurance report included in the Highways Agency year- end financial statements and report which are laid before the House. That report is therefore the most appropriate source of information about the control framework of which the work of the CFC forms part.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England will be reviewing the Terms of Reference and internal reporting arrangements for its Counter Fraud Committee as part of the on-going process of review of its governance framework, risk and internal control framework as an independent company. The Framework Document provides that in doing so it will continue to follow Treasury guidance on tackling fraud.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-03-25T14:51:48.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229215/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229215/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-03-23","Highways Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 19 March 2015 to Question 227614, if he will publish the Counter Fraud Committee's reports to the Audit Committee of the Highways Agency.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","228719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229216","Department for Transport","false","2015-03-25","<p>No information is available prior to the HR casework team being set up in June 2008.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The attached table shows the number of grievances received in the calendar year by each office:-</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-03-25T15:45:56.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229216/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229216/answer","228726 (Table).docx","228726 (Table).docx","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229216/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-03-23","Highways Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many formal grievances were raised against each office of the Highways Agency's North of England management team in each year since 2006.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","228726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229217","Department for Transport","false","2015-03-25","<p>No information is available prior to the HR casework team being set up in June 2008.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the average, shortest and longest number of days for grievances concluded in the calendar year:-</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Average Length</p></td><td><p>443</p></td><td><p>334</p></td><td><p>289</p></td><td><p>183</p></td><td><p>307</p></td><td><p>230</p></td><td><p>171</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Shortest Case</p></td><td><p>346</p></td><td><p>132</p></td><td><p>34</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>48</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Longest Case</p></td><td><p>696</p></td><td><p>477</p></td><td><p>566</p></td><td><p>566</p></td><td><p>497</p></td><td><p>441</p></td><td><p>397</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>When providing this information, the following assumptions have been made:-</p><p>1. North of England includes NW and NE Regional Control Centre and associated outstations, and both Leeds and Manchester offices.</p><p>2. We are unable to confirm whether the grievance related specifically to the management team.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-03-25T15:19:23.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229217/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229217/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-03-23","Highways Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the (a) average, (b) shortest and (c) longest time taken to conclude investigations of grievances made against the Highways Agency's North of England management team was in each year between 2006 and 2014.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","228728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229218","Department for Transport","false","2015-03-25","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>No information is available prior to the HR casework team being set up in June 2008.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the number of grievances received in the calendar year along with the current status:-</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Outcome</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2008</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2009</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Grand Total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Awaiting decision</p></td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td><p>9</p></td><td> </td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Not Available</p></td><td> </td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Informally resolved</p></td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Not upheld</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td> </td><td><p>41</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Partially Upheld</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td> </td><td> </td><td><p>21</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Upheld</p></td><td> </td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td> </td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Withdrawn</p></td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td> </td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Grand Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>7</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>24</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>21</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>22</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>99</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p>When providing this information, the following assumptions have been made:-</p><p>1. North of England includes NW and NE Regional Control Centre and associated outstations, and both Leeds and Manchester offices.</p><p>2. We are unable to confirm whether the grievance related specifically to the management team</p><p>3. Awaiting decision indicates grievances that have been received that are awaiting a decision.</p><p>4. Not available indicates a case that has been concluded but in the timescale given we are unable to confirm the outcome.</p><p>5. Upheld: is defined as the grievance outcome was found in favour of the complainant.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-03-25T15:44:36.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229218/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229218/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-03-23","Highways Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many investigations of grievances raised against the Highways Agency's North of England management team in each year since 2006 (a) were found in favour of the complainant, (b) were found in favour of the Highways Agency, (c) are unresolved and (d) are yet to conclude.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","228727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229219","Department for Transport","false","2015-03-26","<p>The Department commissions a wide range of research to support its objectives. The general presumption is that research results used in the course of the Department’s business should be made available to broaden knowledge and better inform discussion. In a few circumstances (for instance, where the research relates to security matters or where the Department does not hold the necessary rights to publish) such information is not published; but such circumstances are exceptional. Information on publication of the outputs of this research is not collected centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-03-26T13:04:37.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229219/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229219/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-03-23","Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what research his Department has commissioned from external bodies between September 2010 and December 2014 has not been published; when each such report was commissioned; what the nature of the research commissioned for each such report was; from whom each such research report was commissioned; what the value of each such commission was; on what date each such report was received by his Department; for what reason each such research report has not yet been published; and when he plans to publish each such report.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","228842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229220","Department for Transport","false","2015-03-26","<p>Network Rail is an arm’s-length public sector body and the provision of business support to existing tenants affected by Network Rail’s proposed refurbishment of Brixton Arches remains a commercial matter for direct resolution between the parties concerned.</p><p> </p><p>Network Rail advises that the scale of the work, which is likely to take a year, means that businesses will be unable to remain in their current spaces. It understands that this will be a serious upheaval for its tenants. Network Rail is already providing help and advice on the next steps. It will work with each individual occupier, provide business support tailored to each of their individual requirements, and work with them should they wish to return upon completion of the improvements. Network Rail will discuss the options available to them, including the phasing of the works and compensation.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-03-26T11:48:33.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229220/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229220/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-03-23","Network Rail: Brixton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will discuss with Network Rail the need to support businesses currently renting properties from Network Rail in the Brixton railway arches.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","228822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229221","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-03-26","<p>Mandatory reconsideration is an entirely separate process to the new arrangements for dealing with Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) repeat claims. No change to the mandatory reconsideration process is required as a result. We keep the mandatory reconsideration process under review with the aim to improving the process as necessary.</p><p> </p><p>No estimate has been undertaken of the number of individuals previously entitled to claim ESA who will claim Jobseeker's Allowance (JSA) following the changes proposed by the ESA repeat claims project.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has made no specific estimate of the number of individuals previously entitled to ESA who would be entitled to JSA but choose not to claim it following the changes to the benefit rules.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does all that it can to encourage people found fit for work to claim JSA. ESA decision-makers make decision assurance calls which invite claimants to claim JSA where appropriate. Claimants are routed to the contact centre to discuss their claim with an agent. Where such calls are unsuccessful claimants are provided with a written notification of how to call the JSA contact centre to make a claim.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","228848 ; 228849 ; 228850","2015-03-26T08:46:17.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229221/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229221/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-03-23","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reason improving the mandatory reconsideration process was not included within the scope of his Department's employment and support allowance repeat claims project.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","228847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229222","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-03-26","<p>The information requested is not available.</p><p> </p><p>DWP plans to look into what it might be possible to publish on mandatory reconsiderations in the existing regular statistical publications, including information on outcomes. Before decisions are made DWP statisticians need to make sure that the data is accurate and fit for purpose. When a decision has been made and as each publication is ready, we will pre-announce the improvements in 2015 in accordance with the UKSA release protocols.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","228855","2015-03-26T09:17:08.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229222/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229222/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-03-23","Social Security Benefits: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many fit for work decisions were overturned by mandatory reconsideration in each month since October 2008.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","228854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229223","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-03-26","<p>The information requested is not available.</p><p> </p><p>DWP plans to look into what it might be possible to publish on mandatory reconsiderations in the existing regular statistical publications, including information on outcomes. Before decisions are made DWP statisticians need to make sure that the data is accurate and fit for purpose. When a decision has been made and as each publication is ready, we will pre-announce the improvements in 2015 in accordance with the UKSA release protocols.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","228854","2015-03-26T09:17:09.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229223/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229223/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-03-23","Social Security Benefits: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many fit for work decisions overturned by mandatory reconsideration or appeal related to claimants with mental health difficulties in each month since October 2008.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","228855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229224","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-03-26","<p>Mandatory reconsideration is an entirely separate process to the new arrangements for dealing with Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) repeat claims. No change to the mandatory reconsideration process is required as a result. We keep the mandatory reconsideration process under review with the aim to improving the process as necessary.</p><p> </p><p>No estimate has been undertaken of the number of individuals previously entitled to claim ESA who will claim Jobseeker's Allowance (JSA) following the changes proposed by the ESA repeat claims project.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has made no specific estimate of the number of individuals previously entitled to ESA who would be entitled to JSA but choose not to claim it following the changes to the benefit rules.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does all that it can to encourage people found fit for work to claim JSA. ESA decision-makers make decision assurance calls which invite claimants to claim JSA where appropriate. Claimants are routed to the contact centre to discuss their claim with an agent. Where such calls are unsuccessful claimants are provided with a written notification of how to call the JSA contact centre to make a claim.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","228847 ; 228849 ; 228850","2015-03-26T08:46:17.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229224/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229224/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-03-23","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of individuals previously entitled to claim employment and support allowance who will claim jobseeker's allowance following the changes proposed by the employment and support allowance repeat claims project.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","228848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229225","Cabinet Office","false","2015-03-26","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2015-03-26T09:22:54.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229225/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229225/answer","PQ 228823 ONS123.pdf","PQ 228823 ONS123.pdf","ONS Letter to Member - Learning Difficulties","ONS Letter to Member - Learning Difficulties","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229225/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-03-23","Unemployment: Learning Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people with learning difficulties who wished to work but were unemployed there were in (a) Streatham constituency, (b) Lambeth local authority area and (c) the UK in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","228823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229226","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-03-26","<p>Published statistics show that between Q1 2009/10 (the earliest period statistics are available) and Q3 2014/15 (the latest period statistics are available), Her Majesty’s Courts and Tribunals Service (HMCTS) received 1,096,732 Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) appeals. Whilst the vast majority of these claimants would have chosen to continue to receive a payment of ESA pending their appeal, some did choose to remain on Jobseeker’s Allowance. As the latter information is not available it is not possible to provide an exact answer.</p><p> </p><p>Historical information on the average length of time for appeals is not readily available. The most recently published HMCTS statistics state the average (mean) clearance time for Judge and Member ESA/Incapacity Benefit appeals was 22 weeks. Accordingly this would also be the average length of time of payment of ESA pending appeal.</p><p> </p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","228857","2015-03-26T09:09:38.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229226/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229226/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-03-23","Employment and Support Allowance: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many employment and support allowance claimants have received payment of that benefit pending an appeal since October 2008.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","228856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229227","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-03-26","<p>Published statistics show that between Q1 2009/10 (the earliest period statistics are available) and Q3 2014/15 (the latest period statistics are available), Her Majesty’s Courts and Tribunals Service (HMCTS) received 1,096,732 Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) appeals. Whilst the vast majority of these claimants would have chosen to continue to receive a payment of ESA pending their appeal, some did choose to remain on Jobseeker’s Allowance. As the latter information is not available it is not possible to provide an exact answer.</p><p> </p><p>Historical information on the average length of time for appeals is not readily available. The most recently published HMCTS statistics state the average (mean) clearance time for Judge and Member ESA/Incapacity Benefit appeals was 22 weeks. Accordingly this would also be the average length of time of payment of ESA pending appeal.</p><p> </p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","228856","2015-03-26T09:09:38.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229227/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229227/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-03-23","Employment and Support Allowance: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average length of time was that a claimant received payment of employment and support allowance pending appeal in the most recent period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","228857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229228","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-03-26","<p>The Department has not conducted research into the proportion of UK businesses who are aware of Access to Work funding or of the Access to Work Mental Health Service.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2015-03-26T08:37:00.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229228/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229228/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-03-23","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what research his Department has carried out into the proportion of UK businesses who are aware of Access to Work funding which can help people with a disability start work, stay in work, move into self-employment or start a business; and what research his Department has carried out into the proportion of employers who are aware that Access to Work funding can be used to help those with mental health conditions, learning difficulties or disabilities, and autism.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","228824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229229","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-03-26","<p>The Independent Living Fund does not collect or record data on how many personal assistants are employed by its users, either directly or through an agency.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2015-03-26T08:49:46.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229229/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229229/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-03-23","Independent Living Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many personal assistants are employed under the Independent Living Fund.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Corbyn","Islington North","Jeremy Corbyn","228844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229230","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-03-26","<p>The Independent Living Fund (ILF) provides direct cash payments to enable severely disabled people to purchase personal care or help with domestic duties from a care agency or a privately employed personal assistant. Following closure of the Fund in June 2015 funding and responsibility for former ILF users will transfer to local authorities in England and the devolved administrations in Scotland and Wales.</p><p> </p><p>Access to Work provides support for disabled people in work or engaged in a work centred activity, it has limited overlap with the Independent Living Fund and no discernible budget impacts from this change<strong>.</strong></p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2015-03-26T09:06:42.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229230/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229230/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-03-23","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to increase the Access to Work budget upon the closure of the Independent Living Fund in June 2015.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Corbyn","Islington North","Jeremy Corbyn","228845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229231","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-03-26","<p>Mandatory reconsideration is an entirely separate process to the new arrangements for dealing with Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) repeat claims. No change to the mandatory reconsideration process is required as a result. We keep the mandatory reconsideration process under review with the aim to improving the process as necessary.</p><p> </p><p>No estimate has been undertaken of the number of individuals previously entitled to claim ESA who will claim Jobseeker's Allowance (JSA) following the changes proposed by the ESA repeat claims project.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has made no specific estimate of the number of individuals previously entitled to ESA who would be entitled to JSA but choose not to claim it following the changes to the benefit rules.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does all that it can to encourage people found fit for work to claim JSA. ESA decision-makers make decision assurance calls which invite claimants to claim JSA where appropriate. Claimants are routed to the contact centre to discuss their claim with an agent. Where such calls are unsuccessful claimants are provided with a written notification of how to call the JSA contact centre to make a claim.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","228847 ; 228848 ; 228850","2015-03-26T08:46:17.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229231/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229231/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-03-23","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of individuals previously entitled to claim employment and support allowance who will be entitled to but will not claim jobseeker's allowance following the changes proposed by the employment and support allowance repeat claims project.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","228849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229232","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-03-26","<p>DWP operates a continuous planning cycle which incorporates forecast for demand, changes in economic indicators and resource requirements to deliver agreed service standards. Access to Work is part of this planning cycle.</p><p> </p><p>This planning process ensures Access to Work funding is set at a level that enables the scheme to meet existing customer demand and support new customers eligible for support.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2015-03-26T08:59:01.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229232/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229232/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-03-23","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what criteria his Department applies to ensure the level of the Access to Work budget is responsive to need.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Corbyn","Islington North","Jeremy Corbyn","228846"
